# Modifier System

The Modifier System handles temporary stat changes from spells, items, buffs, and effects. It's how stat bonuses work without mutating base values.

## The Core Problem

### Without Modifiers (Bad)

// Base stat
int baseStr = 8;

// Player casts spell: +2 STR
baseStr += 2;  // baseStr = 10

// Player drinks potion: +1 STR
baseStr += 1;  // baseStr = 11

// Spell ends, need to remove it
baseStr -= 2;  // baseStr = 9

// Wait, was it +2? Or was there another bonus?
// Chaos! Can't track sources!


### With Modifiers (Good)

int baseStr = 8;

// Player casts spell: +2 STR
modifiers[ModifierSource.Spell] = 2;

// Player drinks potion: +1 STR
modifiers[ModifierSource.Item] = 1;

// Effective STR = 8 + 2 + 1 = 11

// Spell ends, remove that source
modifiers.Remove(ModifierSource.Spell);

// Effective STR = 8 + 1 = 9

// Clear tracking of what bonuses come from what!


Much better!

## How It Works

### Three Layers


Base Stat (Immutable)
    8
    |
+ Modifiers (Temporary)
    + 2 (Spell: Metamagic)
    + 1 (Item: Ring)
    = +3 total
    |
= Effective Stat (Calculated)
    8 + 3 = 11


The base stat never changes. All bonuses are tracked separately.

### Data Structure


public sealed partial class OE14CharacterStatsComponent : Component
{
    [DataField]
    public int BaseStrength { get; set; } = 5;  // Never changes

    [DataField, AutoNetworkedField]
    public Dictionary StrengthModifiers { get; set; } = new();
    // { Spell: 2, Item: 1, Buff: 0, ... }

    [DataField, AutoNetworkedField]
    public int EffectiveStrength { get; set; } = 5;  // Calculated
}


## Modifier Sources

Each bonus tracks where it came from:


public enum ModifierSource
{
    Spell,   // From equipped magical items
    Spend,   // From spending character points
    Item,    // From wearing equipment
    Buff,    // From temporary effects
    Racial,  // From racial bonuses
    Other
}


This lets you debug: "Why is my INT so high? Show me where the +3 comes from!"

## Adding Modifiers


// Spell gives +2 INT
component.IntModifiers[ModifierSource.Spell] += 2;
RecalculateEffectiveStats(component);

// Item gives +1 VIT
component.VitalityModifiers[ModifierSource.Item] += 1;
RecalculateEffectiveStats(component);

// Racial bonus: +1 DEX (from Goblin)
component.DexterityModifiers[ModifierSource.Racial] += 1;
RecalculateEffectiveStats(component);


### The Recalculation


private void RecalculateEffectiveStats(OE14CharacterStatsComponent component)
{
    // STR: Base + all modifiers
    component.EffectiveStrength = component.BaseStrength
        + component.StrengthModifiers.Values.Sum();

    // Cap at 10
    component.EffectiveStrength = Math.Min(component.EffectiveStrength, MaxStat);
}


## Overflow Protection

What happens if modifiers exceed the stat cap?

### Without Overflow Protection

Base INT: 8
Metamagic spell: +2
Spell effect: +2
= 12 (exceeds max of 10)


The +2 overflow is wasted!

### With Overflow Protection

Base INT: 8
Modifiers: +2 +2 = +4
Effective INT: min(8+4, 10) = 10
Overflow: 4 - 2 = 2
Available Points: +2 (compensation!)


When you overflow, you get compensation points to spend elsewhere!

## Removing Modifiers


// Spell ends, remove spell bonus
component.StrengthModifiers.Remove(ModifierSource.Spell);
RecalculateEffectiveStats(component);

// Multiple sources? Only remove the specific one
component.StrengthModifiers[ModifierSource.Spell] = 0;
RecalculateEffectiveStats(component);

// Clear all modifiers of one type
var spells = component.StrengthModifiers.Where(x => x.Key == ModifierSource.Spell);
foreach (var mod in spells)
    component.StrengthModifiers.Remove(mod.Key);
RecalculateEffectiveStats(component);


## Real Example: Spell Cast


public void CastMetaMagic(EntityUid caster)
{
    var stats = _entityManager.GetComponent(caster);

    // Check: Can player cast? (validates against effective stat)
    if (stats.EffectiveIntelligence < MinINTToCast)
    {
        _chat.SendMessage("Not enough intelligence!");
        return;  // Reject
    }

    // Apply spell bonus
    stats.IntModifiers[ModifierSource.Spell] =
        stats.IntModifiers.GetValueOrDefault(ModifierSource.Spell) + 2;
    RecalculateEffectiveStats(stats);

    // Check overflow
    if (stats.EffectiveIntelligence >= MaxStat)
    {
        int overflow = stats.IntModifiers.Values.Sum() - (MaxStat - stats.BaseIntelligence);
        stats.AvailablePoints += overflow;
    }

    // UI shows: "INT: 8 -> 10 (+2 Spell)"
}


## Displaying Modifiers


Base Stat: 8
Effective Stat: 11

Breakdown:
  + 2 (Spell: Metamagic)
  + 1 (Item: Mage Ring)
  = +3 total

Display format: "INT: 8 -> 11 (+2 Spell, +1 Item)"


Players can always see where bonuses come from.

## Stat Caps

Different stats have different caps:


const int MinStat = 1;
const int MaxStat = 10;
const int NeutralStat = 5;


All stats are capped at 10. If modifiers exceed:

Modifiers: +3
Effective: min(8+3, 10) = 10
Overflow: +1 (becomes available point)


## Stacking Modifiers

Multiple sources stack:


Base VIT: 7

// Spell: +2
modifiers[Spell] = 2;
// Effective: 7 + 2 = 9

// Item: +1
modifiers[Item] = 1;
// Effective: 7 + 2 + 1 = 10

// Buff: +1
modifiers[Buff] = 1;
// Effective: 7 + 2 + 1 + 1 = 11 -> capped at 10
// Overflow: 1 -> available point


No "highest buff wins" complexity. Everything stacks and overflows together.

## Performance

Modifiers are efficient:
- Dictionary lookup is O(1)
- Recalculation is O(n) where n = number of modifier sources (usually fewer than 10)
- Network sync is automatic with the AutoNetworkedField attribute
- No allocations after initial setup

Safe to update every frame if needed.

## Best Practices

[bold]DO:[/bold]
- Always track which source added a modifier
- Recalculate effective stat after changes
- Check overflow and grant compensation points
- Validate against effective stat (not base)
- Use modifiers for ALL temporary bonuses

[bold]DON'T:[/bold]
- Modify base stat directly
- Mix base and modifier calculations
- Forget to handle overflow
- Apply same modifier twice
- Leave old modifiers lingering (clean up)

## Real-World Example: Elf with Spells


Elf base INT: 7

Spell 1: Metamagic T1 (+1 INT)
  Modifiers: { Spell: 1 }
  Effective: 7 + 1 = 8

Spell 2: Metamagic T2 (+1 INT)
  Modifiers: { Spell: 2 }
  Effective: 7 + 2 = 9

Spell 3: Metamagic T3 (+1 INT)
  Modifiers: { Spell: 3 }
  Effective: 7 + 3 = 10 (capped)

Item: Mage Ring (+1 INT)
  Modifiers: { Spell: 3, Item: 1 }
  Effective: min(7 + 3 + 1, 10) = 10
  Overflow: 1 (available point granted)

Buff: Blessing (+2 INT)
  Modifiers: { Spell: 3, Item: 1, Buff: 2 }
  Effective: min(7 + 3 + 1 + 2, 10) = 10
  Overflow: 3 -> 2 available points

Display: "INT: 7 -> 10 (+3 Spell, +1 Item, +2 Buff, overflow: 3)"


Perfect transparency!

